00:05.580 --> 00:17.380
Okay, the tapes are rolling. I will ask you the first question. If you could
give us some background where you grew up, how you got interested in what you

00:17.380 --> 00:31.100
do, and how you came to write science fiction. Okay. I grew up in Chatham, New
Jersey, which is a suburb of New York, about 27, 28 miles west of New York. and

00:31.100 --> 00:42.080
I always thought I was going to be an engineer. My dad was an engineer, an
electrochemical engineer. But for some reason, once I got to college, and I came

00:42.080 --> 00:53.380
to college out here where I am now in Elsa, Principia College, I got into
chemistry as a major and decided that it was too specialized and then somehow or

00:53.380 --> 01:04.020
other switched to English and just went on in English. I had done some reading
of science fiction as a high school student, but then I pretty much dropped it

01:04.020 --> 01:15.240
until about eight years ago. And I was in bed for a while and just started
reading science fiction for entertainment and became fascinated with it all over

01:15.240 --> 01:18.640
again. So that's how I got back into it.

01:22.940 --> 01:34.060
what other kinds of writing do you do now professionally besides science fiction
and fantasy well I write a lot of reviews and quite a bit of poetry some essays

01:34.060 --> 01:35.620
and some scholarly articles

01:38.260 --> 01:47.880
pretty much run the gamut I teach a lot of writing and I try to do the kinds of
writing that I professionally that I ask my students to do so I can give them

01:47.880 --> 02:01.900
examples I had never published fiction before the breaking of Northwall,
though. I felt that quite a gap. I guess it's plugged now. How does this kind of

02:01.900 --> 02:16.280
writing fit in with writing science fiction? It's really very different, because
most of these other kinds of writing are much more exacting, I think, in some

02:16.280 --> 02:29.340
ways. That is, in a sense, science fiction, although it should be good, should
also be easy and entertaining. And so I think there's an atmosphere of fun that

02:29.340 --> 02:40.380
surrounds it, both in the writing and the reading of it. And for me, it's really
entertainment. I can do it when I'm tired late at night. Very often, I sit down

02:40.380 --> 02:51.440
to write, and pretty soon I'm very wide awake. I can't do that with an essay,
certainly not with a poem. I think that writing poetry, as I've done now for

02:51.440 --> 03:07.020
well over 20 years, has helped me a great deal, though, in gaining a feel of the
sounds of words and the kind of sound clusters that evoke certain meanings. and

03:07.020 --> 03:21.560
as you know in poetry every sound, every word is chiseled and worked on and
worried about a great deal more than in entertaining fiction but still I think

03:21.560 --> 03:34.700
the art of poetry feeds over into the other art I think those are the main
differences that I see There is a subcategory of science fiction, which is

03:34.700 --> 03:44.220
science fiction poetry. Have you ever attempted any of this or does that tempt
you to try it? Yeah, I have written some. I used to belong to the Science

03:44.220 --> 04:00.260
Fiction Poetry Association, but I let my membership lapse. And for some reason
or other, my imagination, my poetic imagination, doesn't drift in the direction

04:00.260 --> 04:11.140
of science fiction. Once in a while I'll do something. I find that when I do
write speculative or science fiction poetry, it tends to get very complicated

04:11.140 --> 04:24.280
and hard to understand. And I'm not an obscurantist in poetry. I believe that I
give poetry readings, for example. I don't believe in giving a reading that

04:24.280 --> 04:38.680
mystifies everybody. I like a certain amount of immediacy. So it hasn't worked
very well for me. In the three novels, occasionally there were songs. Were these

04:38.680 --> 04:51.220
original compositions original poems? Yes, yes. They're all original songs, and
some of them are, you know, really just quatrains or hymn stanzas. There's

04:51.220 --> 05:04.980
nothing terribly remarkable. magical. I tried to, especially in the breaking of
Northwall, use a variety of styles, inventing new styles for each of the tribal

05:04.980 --> 05:19.120
groups, and that was kind of fun. The most serious poem, I think, in all three
volumes is one that is sung near the end of Dome in the Forest, And that's

05:19.120 --> 05:27.000
actually a poem I've had around for years, and I think I kind of like it. It's
sung by a character named Tristal.

