07:30.000 --> 07:34.780
books. Yeah, I must admit, It's a sort of form of self-indulgence.

07:38.460 --> 07:46.440
Okay. You mentioned that the breaking of Northwall was your first published
science fiction effort. Yeah. So I'd like to talk a little bit about the

07:46.440 --> 07:56.620
mechanics of that. How long did it take you to... Oh, how did the idea evolve?
How long did it take you to think the idea, work it out, and then start getting

07:56.620 --> 08:09.680
it on paper? Well, it was a very strange experience. It was one of the strangest
experiences I've ever had. I always carry a notebook with me because I do write

08:09.680 --> 08:22.460
a lot and I like to have something ready if I get an idea. And if I'm ever
waiting for something, I use the notebook to amuse myself. I was waiting for a

08:22.460 --> 08:36.620
meeting to start in the beginning of July and this strange image came into my
mind. And so I just started writing it down. And when the meeting did start, I

08:36.620 --> 08:47.100
really didn't hear any of the meeting because the idea was generating. And after
the meeting, I went to my office and cranked a piece of paper in the typewriter

08:47.100 --> 09:00.720
and started typing. And I typed the first three pages of what's now in print and
where the ideas came from. I had no idea. And the rest of the summer, I worked

09:00.720 --> 09:10.000
on it every day. I guess I must have been three or four days into it before I
really realized I was writing a novel. And by September 5th, I had a first

09:10.000 --> 09:22.740
draft, which was substantially what the novel became. I did revise it, but not
heavily. And I just don't know how it happened. I mean, it just sort of came,

09:22.820 --> 09:34.800
and I didn't plot it. I've flotted the other two, but I just sort of let it
happen and would go back to the typewriter every day to find out what was going

09:34.800 --> 09:49.840
to happen next. I never got stuck. I always seemed to know what was going to
happen. One day I went to church and I was trying to work out a battle theme, a

09:49.840 --> 10:01.120
climactic battle with the Tantal. and I guess you're not supposed to go to
church for this reason but I didn't hear anything in church because it all

10:01.120 --> 10:13.160
started coming clear and after church I had lunch and started writing and with
one short break I wrote till midnight and I had finished the battle scene and

10:13.160 --> 10:25.980
written 35 pages which is by far the most I've ever written in one day but
really I was sort of amazed at the experience all along because it seemed to be

10:25.980 --> 10:38.720
happening to me rather than something I was consciously doing and the other
novels took a lot more effort but this one was just sort of handed to me in a

10:38.720 --> 10:50.740
way Your mentioning of the battle scenes brings to mind a question especially at
the climax of the breaking of Northwall, the battles were really drawn out and

10:50.740 --> 11:00.280
the strategy was plotted. The other two books, it was mainly skirmishes and one
-on-one combat, but do you have any experience with either planning battles or

11:00.280 --> 11:08.100
from historical perspectives? Are you interested in that sort of thing? Because
they were very realistic. No, I have absolutely none. I've never been in the

11:08.100 --> 11:19.740
army. I've read very little about that sort of thing. I don't know where that
comes from. I often wondered myself how I keep gravitating toward battle scenes

11:19.740 --> 11:33.920
when I don't think of myself as very belligerent. But I think the reasoning out
of how it ought to be done and what would happen sort of fascinates me. And

11:33.920 --> 11:38.520
sometimes they're useful as metaphors for various kinds of human conflict.

11:44.100 --> 11:54.640
You discussed in quite a bit of detail the geography of the Three Rivers area
where certainly the first one took place and parts of the others. Why did you

11:54.640 --> 12:08.660
locate the three main cities there? Where did that idea come from? Well, I've
lived here two miles downriver from where I put Pelbargan now for 18 years,

12:08.720 --> 12:20.820
and I'm utterly fascinated with this area of the United States. I think I became
that way when I was way back in high school. I read Bernard Devoto's book,

12:21.000 --> 12:33.840
Course of Empire, which is mostly about the Louisiana Purchase and the move
westward, especially Lewis and Clark in their expedition. And the place has

12:33.840 --> 12:46.660
always had a sense of drama to me around here. And also, this particular area
has a fantastic archaeological history. it's the one area in all of North

12:46.660 --> 13:00.660
America that has the most, the densest Indian or prehistoric population. And
I've done a good deal of study of archaeology, too. It just seemed like a

13:00.660 --> 13:16.340
natural place to put a rather settled civilization or culture, rather, and have
these others impinge upon it. So I guess it really emerges from my own

13:16.340 --> 13:28.920
experience here. And I teach American literature, so I'm very aware of the
American continent. I think it's a very dramatic place. So much has happened

13:28.920 --> 13:32.040
here so rapidly.

13:33.940 --> 13:46.740
It's a dramatic place to be. So I guess that's the reason. Really, I come at
science fiction from a different angle from most people. Out of much more of a

13:46.740 --> 14:01.200
literary background than most science fiction writers, and particularly out of
American lit. So I think my books tend to bridge the two types a little more

14:01.200 --> 14:02.160
than most books do.

14:05.220 --> 14:15.560
Probably the thing to me that made the novels most interesting was the
descriptions of the various tribes and their little idiosyncrasies and the

14:15.560 --> 14:33.280
names. Where did you come up with all this? Well, I envisioned the Pelbar as a
group that had been started by a woman named Amanda Pel who had been a,

14:33.380 --> 14:45.980
she's sort of a feminist. And she is a metallurgist, or was, from a caterpillar
tractor up in Peoria. But she survived the holocaust by the fact that she was

14:45.980 --> 15:02.200
spelunking down in the Ozarks. And it would be quite natural for her to set up a
feminist society. and I really I sort of tried to create the Pelbar as a

15:02.200 --> 15:16.260
settled society with what you might call a nesting instinct and a natural
combination of self-protectiveness and non-aggressiveness although they're

15:16.260 --> 15:28.500
certainly capable of great destructiveness but potentially a settled place like
that becomes a kind of mother of civilization. So that was what was in my mind

15:28.500 --> 15:45.960
there. I created the Shumai and Santani out of my memories of, well in part, out
of my memories of the conflict of Caesar and the Celts in Britain. The Shumai

15:45.960 --> 16:04.640
are very Celtic in their behavior because they're enthusiastic artistic, kind of
reckless, and unorganized, whereas the Sentani are much more Roman. They

16:04.640 --> 16:21.580
organize into their star band and do everything in a pattern, organized way, and
I invented some backgrounds for these groups. Shumai as offspring of the

16:21.580 --> 16:37.860
children of one farmer in southwestern Minnesota named Aaron Shumacher. The
Santani the Explorer Scout Troop led by Antonio Santani who was a watchmaker in

16:37.860 --> 16:50.120
Memphis who happened to have a love of Roman history They were on a field trip
to a coal mine in Tennessee and so escaped the Holocaust there and created their

16:50.120 --> 16:52.400
society along quite different lines.

16:55.580 --> 17:11.260
The weapons in the breaking of Northwall really come out of local archaeology
because during most of post-glacial Indian history in this area, if the Indians

17:11.260 --> 17:27.040
were users of spears, only fairly recently, well, 2000 years ago, they begin to
develop bows and arrows. And that coincides with their becoming a more settled

17:27.040 --> 17:39.920
culture adapting to agriculture and that kind of thing. And I guess that culture
shift was all also in the back of my mind, although, you know, The strange thing

17:39.920 --> 17:52.700
about it was I figured all this stuff out after I wrote the book, you know, that
aha, that's where it must have come from, rather than consciously adopting these

17:52.700 --> 18:04.520
things for the book. It might sound strange, but anyway, that's how it happened.
I want to hit some more on that in a minute. okay you've explained kind of the

18:04.520 --> 18:14.620
macroscopic development of the tribes but if we start zeroing in on people the
individuals of the tribes they had their loves and their hates and the rituals

18:14.620 --> 18:25.300
and the religions and the games you must be interested in games at least to put
so many different variations of games in the books and that lended character to

18:25.300 --> 18:34.460
these people too Yes. Well, I have this theory that the

18:34.460 --> 18:49.400
shumai, being in love with the open, in a sense, are not necessarily rendered
stupid by that. And in some cultures, they're really extremely aware of their

18:49.400 --> 19:01.540
surroundings, and they have a great sense of play. so it seemed quite natural to
me that they would develop these games and two of the games for example a star

19:01.540 --> 19:16.980
game and a game of Nana are both functional for them too the one helping them
locate themselves and the other helping them sharpen their reflexes so they're

19:18.420 --> 19:34.240
both games and they're educational tools as well The other interesting tribe to
me was the Emory. Oh, yeah. Are they Italians? Well, there are some Italian in

19:34.240 --> 19:39.920
their background. Yeah, they're located north of Denver, up toward Boulder.

19:43.500 --> 19:57.200
And they're just the people in that area who survived. But the particular reason
for their particular function they have in the book is that I was trying to use,

19:57.340 --> 20:12.080
among other things, various societies as ways of looking at the question of
domination. I mean the Pelbar are a female dominant society. The only Santanis

20:12.080 --> 20:27.700
we see, we never see them at home. And they are sort of a military society but
fairly democratic in their organization. The Shumai are a male dominated society

20:27.700 --> 20:44.120
but kind of mildly so. and I needed a society in which the domination was very
great and the Emory served that function in the book I discovered in writing the

20:44.120 --> 20:55.920
book that I was trying to see what are the effects of domination in society
because every society does dominate in some ways certain groups dominate others

20:55.920 --> 21:12.360
and I discovered that The more severe the domination was, the more danger the
dominators really incurred because they lost a clear grasp of the feelings and

21:12.360 --> 21:27.920
aspirations of the people they were dominating. And Emory are really a study in
that. The situation has grown so top-heavy that it collapses. And I wanted

21:27.920 --> 21:42.580
Jestak, the hero, who seems to operate as a catalyst wherever he appears in the
book, just to be the person who gives it that push that makes it topple. And I

21:42.580 --> 21:53.260
think that was very good of him to do. I tried to indicate that he naturally
didn't cure the society of these habits right away, but they are moving in the

21:53.260 --> 21:56.280
direction of a more reasonable sense of government.

21:59.140 --> 22:12.660
Was Jestak modeled after any historical figure? No, I tried to just make him up.
And I even, I've tried to model characters after people I know, but I've never

22:12.660 --> 22:25.820
been able to make it work. About two pages into the character, they grow so
vivid in so much themselves that they cease being anybody I know about, and just

22:25.820 --> 22:27.280
acquire their own personalities.

22:29.700 --> 22:43.220
I discovered only last year when someone showed me that in the National
Geographic, there is a minor deity in Pakistan named Jestak, and I thought I'd

22:43.220 --> 22:44.080
made the word up.

22:49.440 --> 23:00.680
the ends of the circle my interpretation of it was that it was whimsical
compared to the other two books didn't seem as serious and we learned about all

23:00.680 --> 23:13.940
these strange societies and they were quite odd so it appeared to be whimsical
to me did you have that in mind or is that just my interpretation well, I think

23:13.940 --> 23:30.460
It was somewhat more whimsical. The problem I set for myself there was I asked
what are the skills that a young married couple has to know in order to be

23:30.460 --> 23:44.200
successfully married. and the book starts with a marriage that's just fallen
apart almost immediately and in essence they learn the skills and

23:45.400 --> 24:00.380
as because of the peculiarities of Pelbar society, Aro has much more self
-knowledge than does Stel. What she lacks is a knowledge of the aspects and

24:00.380 --> 24:13.500
virtues of manhood, as well as some of the disagreeable sides of males.
Everything that happens to her in the book instructs her further about the

24:13.500 --> 24:30.920
nature and the validity of men. But still doesn't have a very clear sense of
himself. His experience in my mind is a sort of an odyssey. That is, it's a a

24:30.920 --> 24:44.980
psychological journey and the things he meets are the things I think he has to
learn about himself. The oddest of all the societies is the roti, which is, I'm

24:44.980 --> 24:55.960
not even sure it works, but the curious thing is that most people who read the
book simply take it as a book of a series of adventures and it works for them.

24:57.300 --> 25:12.500
Maybe I oughtn't to confess it, But, you know, if you add an E in front of roti
and a C at the end, you end up with the word erotic. And in essence, this is the

25:12.500 --> 25:28.640
problem, the psychological problem that Stel is brought to confront when he runs
into them. he's now lived through the winter and he's growing more comfortable

25:28.640 --> 25:42.560
in his aloneness and the problem of eroticism arises in his experience he tries
to flee from it somehow it keeps following him and in order to escape it he

25:42.560 --> 25:58.760
decides to be beyond it as I've seen some people do and in a sense this is his
entering into the the Ozar Society, which is a society of old people. And the

25:58.760 --> 26:14.000
problems he encounters there are essentially problems that one encounters with
age, decrepitude, jealousy, inability to function, and impending death. And in

26:14.000 --> 26:25.460
essence, he discovers that he can't really survive in that society or function
in it. in essence, it coughs him up. And as soon as he leaves, along comes the

26:25.460 --> 26:40.180
roti again. And so he tries a new approach to ridding himself of that problem by
just simply killing them. But in killing eroticism, he also kills feeling,

26:40.480 --> 26:55.740
essentially. So he enters into a feelingless period, a period of intense self
-examination. and in the mountains he meets in the character named Skula. He

26:55.740 --> 27:08.160
meets what he might become if he continues those tendencies and gets to have
what I think of as a conversation with himself. And he does a lot of suffering,

27:08.160 --> 27:20.940
but out of this, he emerges with a kind of self-mastery. and everything after
that that he meets, he meets as someone more or less in control of himself.

27:21.760 --> 27:27.580
Which is really what he has had to learn, as I could see of it anyway.

27:31.700 --> 27:42.640
This is something on the spur of the moment as an English student in college
years ago, I was always curious about, OK, you just explained what Stale was

27:42.640 --> 27:53.840
going through through these various devices. Did you sit down before you wrote
the book and said, aha, I'm going to have him develop in this manner? Or is this

27:53.840 --> 28:06.140
kind of a post-mortem analysis of what you did? Did you set out to write this
and this was the symbolism? OK. When I wrote The Breaking of Northwall, so many

28:06.140 --> 28:17.160
people expressed amazement that I didn't sit down and plot it, and I just sort
of wrote it. Sometimes I felt, well, gee, they know more about this than I do,

28:17.300 --> 28:28.060
because most of them were writers. I had better plot the next book. And so I
spend quite a bit of time planning it all out and analyzing the problems that

28:28.060 --> 28:41.040
were to be encountered in the book. So it's a very different kind of book. It's
much more of a planned book. I think I tried to consciously direct it at a

28:41.040 --> 28:57.440
fairly juvenile audience, too. and the themes are all fairly well spelled out
fairly explicitly in the book. I have had hopes that it would begin to be read

28:57.440 --> 29:10.800
in advanced high school or early college classes, and I know I tried it out on a
group of freshmen I taught, which was a rather odd experience but at any rate

29:10.800 --> 29:23.440
they seem to understand it and they all they wrote a paper on it and the
thematic statements were in there so it's much more of a literary production

29:23.440 --> 29:25.940
than North Wolf.

29:30.240 --> 29:40.340
In The Dome in the Forest you have been introduced us to another set of people
the people that have been in the dome for centuries. And you went to great

29:40.340 --> 29:54.700
lengths to portray the advanced knowledge that they might bring as a two-edged
sword. Does this come from your own private feelings? Yes, it does. And also,

29:55.180 --> 30:08.280
one of the main things I was trying to do in the book was to examine the
difference between intuition and logic as means of human understanding. And

30:08.280 --> 30:19.240
there are certain characters in the book, like Stael and Aro, and like Ruthann,
who comes from the dome and almost immediately marries a character named Blue.

30:20.580 --> 30:34.000
They're people who combine, to a certain degree, feeling and thought, or
intuition and logic. And they very quietly succeed in advancing their societies.

30:34.000 --> 30:50.460
But they're also extremes, as represented by Tor the Shumai as a man of
incredible intuition, and Eilin from the Dome as a person of nearly pure logic.

30:51.280 --> 31:07.560
And those two really ought to get together, but they sort of instinctively also
distrust each other. in the end well, in the book Pelbaragon goes through a

31:07.560 --> 31:21.300
severe internal struggle as to whether to accept the Dome people into their
society and in essence, the struggle to me is whether or not the society is

31:21.300 --> 31:33.720
going to turn from being essentially a religious society to being much more of a
technological society and they decide in favor of technology, but it's not

31:33.720 --> 31:46.520
entirely a victory as I see it, just as it isn't in our world. I think what we
see going on in the Falkland Islands now is a good example of the degree to

31:46.520 --> 32:03.180
which technology has outrun the ability to relate to one another as human
beings. And as the book continues, we see the logical people, the merely logical

32:03.180 --> 32:18.120
people, continually making gross mistakes. And the intuitional people,
particularly Tor, finding less and less of a place in the central society of the

32:18.120 --> 32:33.400
Heart River, that is, Talbar. And in the end, Tor and his nephew are sort of
coughed up. They leave. They go essentially exploring, which is what intuition

32:33.400 --> 32:48.980
tends to do. and Eolind remains, but not entirely happily. You know, in essence,
I don't think that either Tor or Eolind will ever be happy because they're too

32:48.980 --> 33:02.880
intense and they're too one-sided. But I tried to portray the assets that you
get with each of these kinds of thoughts and also the liabilities. The merely

33:02.880 --> 33:15.360
logical people people do not perceive H Webb's humanhood when he penetrates the
dome, and they're quite willing to contemplate disrespecting him in order to see

33:15.360 --> 33:27.740
how he works, because they don't have feelings. And, I think, I don't know,
ultimately, without intuition and feelings, without that outreach of sympathy,

33:27.960 --> 33:35.280
we get ourselves in terrible trouble. And yet, we need logic. So that's
essentially what I had in mind.

